/*
Problem: Selection Sort

Given an array of integers, sort the array in ascending order using
the Selection Sort algorithm.

Approach:
1. Assume the current index contains the smallest element.
2. Search for the actual smallest element in the remaining unsorted part.
3. Swap it with the current index.
4. Repeat until the array is sorted.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> selectionSort(vector<int>& nums) {

        int n = nums.size();

        for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {

            int small = i;

            for(int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {

                if(nums[j] < nums[small]) {
                    small = j;
                }
            }

            swap(nums[i], nums[small]);
        }

        return nums;
    }
};

/*
Time Complexity: O(n²)
Space Complexity: O(1)

Mistakes I Made:
1. Started the inner loop from j = 0 instead of j = i + 1, causing the already sorted portion to be searched again.
2. Forgot to return the sorted vector at the end.

Possible Optimization:
Selection Sort always performs O(n²) comparisons, even if the array is already sorted. There is no early-exit optimization like Bubble Sort.
